| best bowling3 = 2/32\n| best bowling4 = 8/47\n| catches/stumpings1 = 0/\u2013\n| catches/stumpings2 = 4/\u2013\n| catches/stumpings3 = 9/\u2013\n| catches/stumpings4 = 9/\u2013\n| source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/774223.html Cricinfo\n| date = 7 March 2020\n}}\n'''Jhye Avon Richardson''' (born 20 September 1996) is an Australian [[cricket]]er. He made his debut in domestic cricket in October 2015, and made his international debut for the [[Australia national cricket team]] in February 2017.<ref name=\"Bio\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/774223.html |title=Jhye Richardson |accessdate=21 October 2015 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>. \n\n==Early and domestic career==\nRichardson is a right-arm fast bowler, and says that, due to his height (178cm) and frame (\"70 odd kilos\"), he was initially discouraged by coaches to become a [[Fast bowling|pace bowler]], a role generally associated with taller and weightier cricketers.<ref name=\"fox\"/> He made his [[List A cricket|List A]] debut for [[Western Australia cricket team|Western Australia]] on 21 October 2015 in the [[2015\u201316 Matador BBQs One-Day Cup]].<ref name=\"ListA\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/895907.html |title=Matador BBQs One-Day Cup, 21st Match: Queensland v Western Australia at Sydney, Oct 21, 2015 |accessdate=21 October 2015 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> In December 2015 he was named in [[2016 Under-19 Cricket World Cup squads|Australia's squad]] for the [[2016 Under-19 Cricket World Cup]].<ref name=\"Australia\">{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-under-19-world-cup-2016/content/story/953415.html |title=Wes Agar, Clinton Hinchliffe in Australia U-19 World Cup squad |accessdate=19 December 2015 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> On 16 January 2016 he made his [[Twenty20]] debut for the [[Perth Scorchers]] in the [[2015\u201316 Big Bash League season|2015\u201316 Big Bash League]].<ref name=\"BBL\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/897755.html |title=Big Bash League, 31st Match: Perth Scorchers v Melbourne Stars at Perth, Jan 16, 2016 |accessdate=16 January 2016 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> He made his [[first-class cricket|first-class]] debut for Western Australia on 15 March 2016 in the [[2015\u201316 Sheffield Shield season|2015\u201316 Sheffield Shield]].<ref name=\"FC\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/895967.html |title=Sheffield Shield, 28th Match: Queensland v Western Australia at Brisbane, Mar 15\u201318, 2016 |accessdate=15 March 2016 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2016\u201317 Big Bash League season|2016-17 Big Bash League]] Richardson claimed 11 wickets for the Scorchers and was named player of the match in the final after taking 3/30 as the Scorchers defeated the Sydney Sixers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cricket.com.au/news/jhye-richardson-perth-scorchers-big-bash-league-bbl06-final-justin-langer-behrendorff-sydney-sixers/2017-01-29|title=Jhye justifies JL's meditative judgement|website=cricket.com.au|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> \n\nIn November 2018, Richardson took a career best 8/47 in the first innings against New South Wales at Optus Stadium.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/cricket/wa-s-richardson-stars-in-shield-with-eight-wickets-20181127-p50irp.html|title=WA's Richardson stars in Shield with eight wickets|last=Chadwick|first=Justin|date=2018-11-27|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>  \n\n==International career==\nIn February 2017 Richardson was named in Australia's [[Twenty20 International]] (T20I) squad for their series [[Sri Lankan cricket team in Australia in 2016\u201317|against Sri Lanka]].<ref name=\"AusSquad\">{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/australia-v-sri-lanka-2016-17/content/story/1080449.html |title=Klinger, Paine in Australia's T20 squad |accessdate=1 February 2017 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> He made his [[Twenty20 International]] (T20I) debut for Australia against Sri Lanka at [[Kardinia Park (stadium)|Kardinia Park]], [[Geelong]] on 19 February 2017.<ref name=\"T20I\">{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/1001351.html |title=Sri Lanka tour of Australia, 2nd T20I: Australia v Sri Lanka at Geelong, Feb 19, 2017 |accessdate=19 February 2017 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, he was named in Australia's [[One Day International]] (ODI) squad for their series [[English cricket team in Australia in 2017\u201318|against England]].<ref name=\"AusODI\">{{cite web |url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/586746 |title=Lynn replaces Maxwell in Australia ODI squad |accessdate=3 January 2018 |work=International Cricket Council}}</ref> He made his ODI debut for Australia against England on 19 January 2018.<ref name=\"ODI\">{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/1072311.html |title=2nd ODI (D/N), England tour of Australia and New Zealand at Brisbane, Jan 19 2018 |accessdate=19 January 2018 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> Later in the same month, he was named in Australia's [[Test cricket|Test]] squad for their series [[Australian cricket team in South Africa in 2017\u201318|against South Africa]] in March 2018, however, he did not play.<ref name=\"AusTest\">{{cite web |url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/601826 |title=Richardson, Holland in Australia squad for South Africa Tests |accessdate=22 January 2018 |work=International Cricket Council}}</ref> In April 2018, he was awarded a national contract by [[Cricket Australia]] for the 2018\u201319 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/australia/content/story/1142958.html |title=Carey, Richardson gain contracts as Australia look towards World Cup |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=11 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cricket.com.au/news/cricket-australia-contract-list-centrally-salary-upgrade-men-2018-19-tim-paine-marsh-starc-cummins/2018-04-11 |title=Five new faces on CA contract list |work=Cricket Australia |accessdate=11 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, Richardson was named in the squad for the ODI series against [[India national cricket team|India]]. He played the first game at the [[Sydney cricket ground|Sydney Cricket Ground]] and returned with his career best figures of 4/26, including the wicket of the Indian captain [[Virat Kohli]], to help Australia to its 1,000th international win across all formats.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/cricket/richardson-turns-tables-on-india-in-morale-boosting-win-for-australia-20190112-p50r08.html|title=Richardson turns tables on India in morale-boosting win for Australia|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=12 January 2019}}</ref> Later the same month, Richardson was added to Australia's [[Test cricket|Test]] squad for the series [[Sri Lankan cricket team in Australia in 2018\u201319|against Sri Lanka]], replacing the injured [[Josh Hazlewood]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/25796504/hazlewood-sri-lanka-tests-back-injury-richardson-called-up |title=Hazlewood out of Sri Lanka Tests with back injury; Richardson called up |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=19 January 2019}}</ref> He made his Test debut for Australia against [[Sri Lanka national cricket team|Sri Lanka]] on 24 January 2019, taking three wickets in the first innings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/1145000.html |title=1st Test (D/N), Sri Lanka tour of Australia at Brisbane, Jan 24\u201328 2019 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=24 January 2019}}</ref> He had his [[baggy green cap]] presented by [[Damien Fleming]]. \n\nHe was awarded the Bradman Young Cricketer of the Year at the [[Allan Border Medal]] ceremony by [[Cricket Australia]] in 2018.<ref>https://www.cricketaustralia.com.au/about/awards-and-events/australian-cricket-awards</ref>\n\nRichardson played in the final three matches of [[Australian cricket team in India in 2018\u201319|Australia's ODI series against India in March 2019]], claiming 8 wickets as Australia came back from an 0-2 series deficit to eventually win the series 3-2.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wwos.nine.com.au/cricket/aussies-beat-india-3-2-in-odi-series/911a3225-b50f-4cf1-a9d8-18a39a8667ef|title=Aussies complete historic comeback win over India|website=wwos.nine.com.au|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> \n\nIn the subsequent [[Australian cricket team against Pakistan in the UAE in 2018\u201319|series against Pakistan in the UAE in March 2019]], Richardson dislocated his shoulder in the second match diving in the outfield.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wwos.nine.com.au/cricket/aussie-quick-jhye-richardson-hurts-arm/b2d43921-9464-41a2-979d-b0407f079156|title=Injury disaster strikes young Aussie paceman|website=wwos.nine.com.au|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Despite this, in April 2019 he was named in [[2019 Cricket World Cup squads#Australia|Australia's squad]] for the [[2019 Cricket World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/26526151/smith-warner-make-world-cup-return-handscomb-hazlewood-out |title=Smith and Warner make World Cup return; Handscomb and Hazlewood out |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1178345 |title=Smith, Warner named in Australia World Cup squad |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref> The [[International Cricket Council]] (ICC) named him as one of the five exciting talents making their Cricket World Cup debut.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1201658 |title=Cricket World Cup 2019: Debutant watch |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=28 April 2019}}</ref> However, he was later ruled out of the tournament and was replaced in the squad by [[Kane Richardson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/26695428/jhye-richardson-world-cup,-kane-called-up |title=Jhye Richardson out of World Cup, Kane called up |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nRichardson made his international comeback on March 7 2020 in the 3rd ODI against South Africa as Pat Cummins and Mitchell Starc were rested, returning figures of 0/58 from 10 overs. \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cricinfo|id=774223}}\n\n{{Australia Squad 2019 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{Perth Scorchers current squad}}\n{{Western Warriors squad}}\n{{Perth Scorchers 2016\u201317 BBL Champions}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Richardson, Jhye}}\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australia Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:Australian cricketers]]\n[[Category:Australia One Day International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Australia Twenty20 International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2019 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Perth Scorchers cricketers]]\n[[Category:Western Australia cricketers]]\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jhye_Richardson"}
{"title_page": "2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (OFC\u2013CONMEBOL play-off)", "text_new": "{{Infobox football match\n| title                   = 2002 FIFA World Cup qualification <br> ([[CONMEBOL]]\u2013[[Oceania Football Confederation|OFC]] play-off)\n| image                   = \n| event                   = [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification]]\n| team1                   = [[Australia national association football team|Australia]]\n| team1association        = {{flagicon|Australia|size=30px}}\n| team1score              = 1\n| team2                   = [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]]\n| team2association        = {{flagicon|Uruguay|size=30px}}\n| team2score              = 3\n| details                 = Uruguay won 3\u20131 on aggregate\n| firstleg                = First leg\n| team1score1             = 1\n| team2score1             = 0\n| details1                = \n| date1                   = 20 November 2001\n| stadium1                = [[Melbourne Cricket Ground|MCG]]\n| city1                   = [[Melbourne]]\n| man_of_the_match1a      = \n| man_of_the_match1atitle = \n| man_of_the_match1b      = \n| man_of_the_match1btitle = \n| referee1                = [[Graziano Cesari]] ([[Italian Football Federation|Italy]])\n| attendance1             = 84,656\n| weather1                = Partly cloudy<br />{{convert|15|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}}<ref>{{cite web|title=History for Melbourne Airport, VC|url=http://www.wunderground.com/history/airport/MEL/2001/11/20/DailyHistory.html?req_city=NA&req_state=NA&req_statename=NA|publisher=wunderground.com|date=2001-11-20|accessdate=2013-04-02}}</ref>\n| secondleg               = Second leg\n| team1score2             = 0\n| team2score2             = 3\n| details2                = \n| date2                   = 25 November 2001\n| stadium2                = [[Estadio Centenario]]\n| city2                   = [[Montevideo]]\n| man_of_the_match2a      = \n| man_of_the_match2atitle = \n| man_of_the_match2b      = \n| man_of_the_match2btitle = \n| referee2                = [[Ali Bujsaim]] ([[United Arab Emirates Football Association|UAE]])\n| attendance2             = 62,000\n| weather2                = Clear<br />{{convert|16|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}}<ref>{{cite web|title=History for Montevideo, Uruguay|url=http://www.wunderground.com/history/airport/MVD/2001/11/25/DailyHistory.html?req_city=NA&req_state=NA&req_statename=NA|publisher=wunderground.com|date=2001-11-25|accessdate=2013-04-02}}</ref>\n| television              = \n| previous                = \n| next                    = \n}}\nThe '''[[2002 FIFA World Cup]] [[CONMEBOL]]\u2013[[Oceania Football Confederation|OFC]] qualification play-off''' was a [[Two-legged tie|two-legged]] home-and-away tie between the winners of the [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (OFC)|Oceania qualifying tournament]], [[Australia national association football team|Australia]], and the fifth-placed team from the [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|South American qualifying tournament]], [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]]. The games were played on 20 November and 25 November 2001 in [[Melbourne]] and [[Montevideo]] respectively. Australia was hoping to play in the FIFA World Cup for the first time since [[1974 FIFA World Cup|1974]] and Uruguay since [[1990 FIFA World Cup|1990]].\n\n==Background==\n{|  style=\"width:100%; text-align:center;\"\n|-  style=\"vertical-align:top; background:#9cf;\"\n!colspan=2 style=\"width:1*\"|Uruguay\n!Round\n!colspan=2 style=\"width:1*\"|Australia\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\"|\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:175px;\"|Team\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip| Pld | Played}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip| W | Won}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip| D | Drawn}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip| L | Lost}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip| GF | Goals for}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip| GA | Goals against}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip| GD | Goal difference}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip| Pts | Points}}\n|- style=\"backgroun