{"title_page": "Akam (wrestler)", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian professional and amateur wrestler}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name        = Akam\n|image       = Akam NXT tag team champion.jpg\n|caption     = Akam as [[NXT Tag Team Championship|NXT Tag Team Champion]] in February 2017\n|names       = '''Akam'''<ref name=WWE>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/akam|title=Akam bio|accessdate=November 20, 2018|publisher=[[WWE]]}}</ref><br>Sunny Dhinsa\n|birth_name = Sunny Dhinsa\n|height      = 6 ft 3 in<ref name=\"WWE\"/>\n|weight      = 290 lb<ref name=\"WWE\"/>\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1993|5|20}}\n|birth_place = [[Abbotsford, British Columbia]], Canada\n|resides     =\n|alma_mater = [[Simon Fraser University]]\n|billed      = [[Punjab, India]]\n|trainer     = [[WWE Performance Center]]\n|debut       = April 4, 2015\n}}\n{{MedalTableTop}}\n{{MedalSport|[[Freestyle wrestling|Men's freestyle wrestling]]}}\n{{MedalCountry| Canada}}\n{{MedalCompetition| Pan American Games}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2011 Pan American Games|2011 Guadalajara]]|[[Wrestling at the 2011 Pan American Games \u2013 Men's Freestyle 120 kg|120&nbsp;kg]]}}\n{{MedalBottom}}\n\n'''Sunny Dhinsa''' (born May 20, 1993) is a Canadian [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]] and former [[amateur wrestling|amateur wrestler]]. He is signed to [[WWE]], where he performs on the [[Raw (WWE brand)|Raw brand]] under the [[ring name]] '''Akam'''. He is one-half of the former [[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship|WWE Raw Tag Team Champions]], along with [[Rezar (wrestler)|Rezar]] as [[The Authors of Pain|AOP]] (formerly known as Authors of Pain). He previously performed on the [[WWE NXT|NXT]] brand, winning the [[NXT Tag Team Championship|NXT Tag Team Champion]] and [[Dusty Rhodes Tag Team Classic]] winner (with Rezar).\n\n==Early life and amateur wrestling career==\nBorn in [[Abbotsford, British Columbia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wrestlingdata.com/index.php?befehl=bios&wrestler=29575 |title=The World's Largest Wrestling Database |website=Wrestlingdata.com |date= |accessdate=November 15, 2016}}</ref> Dhinsa attended [[Simon Fraser University]], where he was a standout collegiate wrestler. He won the Canadian national [[freestyle wrestling]] champion in 2011, 2012 and 2013 in the heavyweight category. He won a gold medal in the 115&nbsp;kg category at the [[2009 Canada Summer Games]], and a silver medal at the [[2011 Pan American Games]] in [[Guadalajara]]. Dhinsa competed in the qualification tournament for the [[2012 Summer Olympics]], missing out on qualification after losing to [[Dremiel Byers]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.abbynews.com/sports/144283825.html |title=Dhinsa falls short at Olympic wrestling qualifer [sic] \u2013 Abbotsford News |website=Abbynews.com |date=March 26, 2012 |accessdate=November 15, 2016}}</ref> He was considered a prospect for the [[2016 Summer Olympics]] but left amateur wrestling after being offered a contract with [[WWE]] in 2014, having been scouted for the company by [[Gerald Brisco]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2013/09/11/21115126.html |title=CANOE \u2013 SLAM! Sports \u2013 Wrestling \u2013 Olympic wrestling's lifeline is good for the pros too |website=Slam.canoe.com |date= |accessdate=November 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Professional wrestling career==\n=== NXT (2014\u20132018) ===\n{{Main article|The Authors of Pain}}\nIn October 2014, Dhinsa was reported to have signed a contract with [[WWE]] and would begin training to become a professional wrestler at the [[WWE Performance Center]]. He made his in-ring debut at a [[NXT (WWE brand)|NXT]] [[house show]] in [[Orlando, Florida]] on April 4, 2015, competing in a battle royal, which was won by [[Scott Dawson (wrestler)|Scott Dawson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestlezone.com/news/568779-wwe-nxt-live-event-results-44 |title=WWE NXT Live Event Results (4/4): Orlando, FL; Zayn vs Dawson |website=Wrestlezone.com |date=April 5, 2015 |accessdate=November 15, 2016}}</ref> By February 2016 Dhinsa had formed a tag team with [[Rezar (wrestler)|Gzim Selmani]]<ref>\"NXT Tampa, FL, live results: Sami Zayn vs. Manny Andrade for the first time\"</ref> and they became known as the '''Authors of Pain''' in April 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=4/22 WWE NXT in Tampa Results \u2013 TMDK & Nikki Storm make NXT debuts, A-Riley vs. Dillinger main event, No Way Jose, Mandy Rose|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/04/23/422-wwe-nxt-in-tampa-results-tmdk-nikki-storm-make-nxt-debuts-a-riley-vs-dillinger-main-event-no-way-jose-mandy-rose/|publisher=[[Pro Wrestling Torch]]|accessdate=June 18, 2016|date=April 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nDhinsa and Selmani (billed as Akam and Rezar) made their televised ''[[WWE NXT|NXT]]'' debuts on June 8, 2016 at [[NXT TakeOver: The End]];<ref>{{cite web|last1=Johnson|first1=Mike|title=Dillinger has strong showing: Ongoing NXT TakeOver \u2013 The End blog|url=http://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=102567|website=pwinsider.com|accessdate=June 14, 2016}}</ref> following the [[NXT Tag Team Championship]] match, they attacked former champions [[American Alpha]] ([[Chad Gable]] and [[Jason Jordan]]) before being joined on stage by veteran manager [[Paul Ellering]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-news/nxt-takeover-live-results-samoa-joe-vs-finn-balor-cage-match-nakamura-vs-austin-aries|title=NXT TakeOver live results: Samoa Joe vs. Finn Balor cage match; Nakamura vs. Austin Aries|accessdate=June 9, 2016|publisher=[[Wrestling Observer]]|date=June 8, 2016}}</ref> The duo had a push during his time in NXT, winning the [[Dusty Rhodes Tag Team Classic#2016 Tournament|Dusty Rhodes Tag Team Classic]], after defeating [[The Mighty Don't Kneel|TM-61]] at [[NXT TakeOver: Toronto (2016)|NXT TakeOver: Toronto]] and winning at [[NXT TakeOver: San Antonio]] the [[NXT Tag Team Championship]] when they defeated [[DIY (professional wrestling)|#DIY]]. The duo retained the titles at [[NXT TakeOver: Orlando]] (by defeating #DIY and [[The Revival (professional wrestling)|The Revival]] in a [[Professional wrestling tag team match types#Three-way elimination tag team match|triple threat tag team elimination match]] by eliminating both teams) and [[NXT TakeOver: Chicago]] (by defeating #DIY) in a ladder match to retain the titles. The duo turned [[Face (professional wrestling)|face]] on August 9 edition of ''NXT'' after being attacked by [[Sanity (professional wrestling)|SAnitY]]. At [[NXT TakeOver: Brooklyn III]], the Authors of Pain lost the titles to SAnitY at [[NXT TakeOver: WarGames (2017)|NXT TakeOver: WarGames]], Authors of Pain and [[Roderick Strong]] competed in a 3 team [[WarGames match]] which was won by [[The Undisputed Era]]. At [[NXT TakeOver: Philadelphia]], Authors of Pain got a rematch but failed to win back the titles. At [[NXT TakeOver: New Orleans]], Authors of Pain competed in a Triple threat tag team match for the NXT Tag Team Championship and Dusty Rhodes Tag Team Classic trophy which was won by The Undisputed Era (Adam Cole and Kyle O'Reilly).\n\n===Raw (2018\u2013present)===\nOn the April 9 episode of [[Raw (WWE brand)|Raw]], The Authors of Pain, along with Ellering, made their main roster debut, defeating [[Heath Slater]] and [[Rhyno]]. After the match, Akam and Rezar ended their partnership with Ellering by pushing him away and leaving him ringside as they returned backstage.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Benigno |first1=Anthony |title=The Authors of Pain def. Heath Slater & Rhyno |url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-04-09/article/the-authors-of-pain-def-heath-slater-rhyno |website=WWE.com |accessdate=April 9, 2018}}</ref> On the September 3 episode of ''Raw'', The Authors of Pain, now under the shortened name of \"AOP\", were accompanied to the ring by the [[WWE 205 Live|205 Live]] General Manager, [[Rockstar Spud|Drake Maverick]], who announced himself as their new manager.<ref>{{cite web |title=AOP def. Keith Thompson & Jimmy James |url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-09-03#full-detail-40048107 |website=WWE.com |accessdate=September 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn the November 5 episode of Raw, The Authors of Pain defeated [[Seth Rollins]] in a handicap match to win the Raw Tag Team Championship for the first time. They went on to defeat [[WWE SmackDown Tag Team Championship|SmackDown's Tag Team Champions]] [[Cesaro and Sheamus]] in an interbrand Champion vs Champion match at [[Survivor Series (2018)|Survivor Series]]. They lost the titles to [[Bobby Roode]] and [[Chad Gable]] on the December 10 episode of Raw.  In January 2019 Akam suffered an undisclosed leg injury that reportedly would keep him out for \"at least a few months\".<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.fightful.com/wrestling/report-akam-authors-pain-out-leg-injury |title = Report: Akam of the Authors of Pain Undergoes Knee Surgery; Timetable for Return is Two Months &#124; Fightful Wrestling}}</ref> He would be cleared to return to action in May, however the team has yet to return to action.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.fightful.com/wrestling/report-akam-authors-pain-cleared-return-ring-competition |title = Report: Akam of the Authors of Pain Cleared to Return to In-Ring Competition &#124; Fightful Wrestling}}</ref> He and Rezar returned to action at [[Super ShowDown (2019)|Super ShowDown]] on June 7, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.wrestlinginc.com/news/2019/06/wwe-superstars-return-to-action-in-50-man-battle-royal-at-654969/ |title = WWE Superstars Return to Action at Super ShowDown, Updated List of Participants|date = June 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, AOP began appearing in vignettes, warning of their return. During the [[2019 WWE Draft]] in October, AOP went undrafted, becoming free agents and able to choose which brand to sign with. Three days after the draft's conclusion, AOP signed with Raw, remaining on the brand. Then, they started allying with [[Seth Rollins]] after they helped beat down [[Kevin Owens]] on the Raw after [[Survivor Series (2019)]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/videos/breaking-news-regarding-wwe-crown-jewel-free-agency-and-the-intercontinental-title-wwe-now|title=Breaking news regarding WWE Crown Jewel, free agency and the Intercontinental Title: WWE Now|date=October 17, 2019|work=[[WWE]].com|accessdate=October 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Championship and accomplishments ==\n* '''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n** Ranked No. 204 of the top 500 wrestlers in the [[PWI 500]] in 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=97&nr=230#2018|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated (PWI) 500 for 2018|accessdate=September 25, 2018|work=cagematch.net}}</ref>\n* '''[[WWE]]'''\n** [[NXT Tag Team Championship]] ([[List of NXT Tag Team Champions#Reigns|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[Rezar (wrestler)|Rezar]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/titlehistory/nxt-tag-team-championship|title=NXT Tag Team Championship|work=WWE|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n** [[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship]] ([[List of WWE Raw Tag Team Champions|1 time]]) \u2013 with Rezar<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/titlehistory/raw-tag-team-championship|title=Raw Tag Team Championship|work=WWE|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n** [[Dusty Rhodes Tag Team Classic]] (2016) \u2013 with Rezar\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{WWE superstar}}\n* {{Professional wrestling profiles}}\n\n{{WWE personnel}}\n{{WWE Tag Team Championship}}\n{{NXT Tag Team Championship}}\n{{Dusty Rhodes Tag Team Classic Winners}}\n\n[[Category:Canadian male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Canadian male sport wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Abbotsford, British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestlers from British Columbia]]\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Wrestlers at the 2011 Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in wrestling]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games silver medalists for Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian professional and amateur wrestler}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name        = Akam\n|image       = Akam NXT tag team champion.jpg\n|caption     = Akam as [[NXT Tag Team Championship|NXT Tag Team Champion]] in February 2017\n|names       = '''Akam'''<ref name=WWE>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/akam|title=Akam bio|accessdate=November 20, 2018|publisher=[[WWE]]}}</ref><br>Sunny Dhinsa\n|birth_name = Sunny Dhinsa\n|height      = 6 ft 3 in<ref name=\"WWE\"/>\n|weight      = 290 lb<ref name=\"WWE\"/>\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1993|5|20}}\n|birth_place = [[Abbotsford, British Columbia]], Canada\n|resides     =\n|alma_mater = [[Simon Fraser University]]\n|billed      = [[Punjab, India]]\n|trainer     = [[WWE Performance Center]]\n|debut       = April 4, 2015\n}}\n{{MedalTableTop}}\n{{MedalSport|[[Freestyle wrestling|Men's freestyle wrestling]]}}\n{{MedalCountry| Canada}}\n{{MedalCompetition| Pan American Games}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2011 Pan American Games|2011 Guadalajara]]|[[Wrestling at the 2011 Pan American Games \u2013 Men's Freestyle 120 kg|120&nbsp;kg]]}}\n{{MedalBottom}}\n\n'''Sunny Dhinsa''' (born May 20, 1993) is a Canadian [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]] and former [[amateur wrestling|amateur wrestler]]. He is signed to [[WWE]], where he performs on the [[Raw (WWE brand)|Raw brand]] under the [[ring name]] '''Akam'''. He is one-half of the former [[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship|WWE Raw Tag Team Champions]], along with [[Rezar (wrestler)|Rezar]] as [[The Authors of Pain|AOP]] (formerly known as Authors of Pain). He previously performed on the [[WWE NXT|NXT]] brand, winning the [[NXT Tag Team Championship|NXT Tag Team Champion]] and [[Dusty Rhodes Tag Team Classic]] winner (with Rezar).\n\n==Early life and amateur wrestling career==\nBorn in [[Abbotsford, British Columbia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wrestlingdata.com/index.php?befehl=bios&wrestler=29575 |title=The World's Largest Wrestling Database |website=Wrestlingdata.com |date= |accessdate=November 15, 2016}}</ref> Dhinsa attended [[Simon Fraser University]], where he was a standout collegiate wrestler. He won the Canadian national [[freestyle wrestling]] champion in 2011, 2012 and 2013 in the heavyweight category. He won a gold medal in the 115&nbsp;kg category at the [[2009 Canada Summer Games]], and a silver medal at the [[2011 Pan American Games]] in [[Guadalajara]]. Dhinsa competed in the qualification tournament for the [[2012 Summer Olympics]], missing out on qualification after losing to [[Dremiel Byers]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.abbynews.com/sports/144283825.html |title=Dhinsa falls short at Olympic wrestling qualifer [sic] \u2013 Abbotsford News |website=Abbynews.com |date=March 26, 2012 |accessdate=November 15, 2016}}</ref> He was considered a prospect for the [[2016 Summer Olympics]] but left amateur wrestling after being offered a contract with [[WWE]] in 2014, having been scouted for the company by [[Gerald Brisco]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2013/09/11/21115126.html |title=CANOE \u2013 SLAM! Sports \u2013 Wrestling \u2013 Olympic wrestling's lifeline is good for the pros too |website=Slam.canoe.com |date= |accessdate=November 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Professional wrestling career==\n=== NXT (2014\u20132018) ===\n{{Main article|The Authors of Pain}}\nIn October 2014, Dhinsa was reported to have signed a contract with [[WWE]] and would begin training to become a professional wrestler at the [[WWE Performance Center]]. He made his in-ring debut at a [[NXT (WWE brand)|NXT]] [[house show]] in [[Orlando, Florida]] on April 4, 2015, competing in a battle royal, which was won by [[Scott Dawson (wrestler)|Scott Dawson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestlezone.com/news/568779-wwe-nxt-live-event-results-44 |title=WWE NXT Live Event Results (4/4): Orlando, FL; Zayn vs Dawson |website=Wrestlezone.com |date=April 5, 2015 |accessdate=November 15, 2016}}</ref> By February 2016 Dhinsa had formed a tag team with [[Rezar (wrestler)|Gzim Selmani]]<ref>\"NXT Tampa, FL, live results: Sami Zayn vs. Manny Andrade for the first time\"</ref> and they became known as the '''Authors of Pain''' in April 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=4/22 WWE NXT in Tampa Results \u2013 TMDK & Nikki Storm make NXT debuts, A-Riley vs. Dillinger main event, No Way Jose, Mandy Rose|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/04/23/422-wwe-nxt-in-tampa-results-tmdk-nikki-storm-make-nxt-debuts-a-riley-vs-dillinger-main-event-no-way-jose-mandy-rose/|publisher=[[Pro Wrestling Torch]]|accessdate=June 18, 2016|date=April 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nDhinsa and Selmani (billed as Akam and Rezar) made their televised ''[[WWE NXT|NXT]]'' debuts on June 8, 2016 at [[NXT TakeOver: The End]];<ref>{{cite web|last1=Johnson|first1=Mike|title=Dillinger has strong showing: Ongoing NXT TakeOver \u2013 The End blog|url=http://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=102567|website=pwinsider.com|accessdate=June 14, 2016}}</ref> following the [[NXT Tag Team Championship]] match, they attacked former champions [[American Alpha]] ([[Chad Gable]] and [[Jason Jordan]]) before being joined on stage by veteran manager [[Paul Ellering]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-news/nxt-takeover-live-results-samoa-joe-vs-finn-balor-cage-match-nakamura-vs-austin-aries|title=NXT TakeOver live results: Samoa Joe vs. Finn Balor cage match; Nakamura vs. Austin Aries|accessdate=June 9, 2016|publisher=[[Wrestling Observer]]|date=June 8, 2016}}</ref> The duo had a push during his time in NXT, winning the  [[Dusty Rhodes Tag Team Classic#2016 Tournament|Dusty Rhodes Tag Team Classic]], after defeating [[The Mighty Don't Kneel|TM-61]] at [[NXT TakeOver: Toronto (2016)|NXT TakeOver: Toronto]] and winning at [[NXT TakeOver: San Antonio]] the [[NXT Tag Team Championship]] when they defeated [[DIY (professional wrestling)|#DIY]]. The duo retained the titles at [[NXT TakeOver: Orlando]] (by defeating #DIY and [[The Revival (professional wrestling)|The Revival]] in a [[Professional wrestling tag team match types#Three-way elimination tag team match|triple threat tag team elimination match]] by eliminating both teams) and [[NXT TakeOver: Chicago]] (by defeating #DIY) in a ladder match to retain the titles. The duo turned [[Face (professional wrestling)|face]] on August 9 edition of ''NXT'' after being attacked by [[Sanity (professional wrestling)|SAnitY]]. At [[NXT TakeOver: Brooklyn III]], the Authors of Pain lost the titles to SAnitY at [[NXT TakeOver: WarGames (2017)|NXT TakeOver: WarGames]], Authors of Pain and [[Roderick Strong]] competed in a 3 team [[WarGames match]] which was won by [[The Undisputed Era]]. At [[NXT TakeOver: Philadelphia]], Authors of Pain got a rematch but failed to win back the titles. At [[NXT TakeOver: New Orleans]], Authors of Pain competed in a Triple threat tag team match for the NXT Tag Team Championship and Dusty Rhodes Tag Team Classic trophy which was won by The Undisputed Era (Adam Cole and Kyle O'Reilly).\n\n===Raw (2018\u2013present)===\nOn the April 9 episode of [[Raw (WWE brand)|Raw]], The Authors of Pain, along with Ellering, made their main roster debut, defeating [[Heath Slater]] and [[Rhyno]]. After the match, Akam and Rezar ended their partnership with Ellering by pushing him away and leaving him ringside as they returned backstage.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Benigno |first1=Anthony |title=The Authors of Pain def. Heath Slater & Rhyno |url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-04-09/article/the-authors-of-pain-def-heath-slater-rhyno |website=WWE.com |accessdate=April 9, 2018}}</ref> On the September 3 episode of ''Raw'', The Authors of Pain, now under the shortened name of \"AOP\", were accompanied to the ring by the [[WWE 205 Live|205 Live]] General Manager, [[Rockstar Spud|Drake Maverick]], who announced himself as their new manager.<ref>{{cite web |title=AOP def. Keith Thompson & Jimmy James |url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-09-03#full-detail-40048107 |website=WWE.com |accessdate=September 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn the November 5 episode of Raw, The Authors of Pain defeated [[Seth Rollins]] in a handicap match to win the Raw Tag Team Championship for the first time. They went on to defeat [[WWE SmackDown Tag Team Championship|SmackDown's Tag Team Champions]] [[Cesaro and Sheamus]] in an interbrand Champion vs Champion match at [[Survivor Series (2018)|Survivor Series]]. They lost the titles to [[Bobby Roode]] and [[Chad Gable]] on the December 10 episode of Raw.  In January 2019 Akam suffered an undisclosed leg injury that reportedly would keep him out for \u201cat least a few months\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.fightful.com/wrestling/report-akam-authors-pain-out-leg-injury |title = Report: Akam of the Authors of Pain Undergoes Knee Surgery; Timetable for Return is Two Months &#124; Fightful Wrestling}}</ref> He would be cleared to return to action in May, however the team has yet to return to action.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.fightful.com/wrestling/report-akam-authors-pain-cleared-return-ring-competition |title = Report: Akam of the Authors of Pain Cleared to Return to In-Ring Competition &#124; Fightful Wrestling}}</ref> He and Rezar returned to action at [[Super ShowDown (2019)|Super ShowDown]] on June 7, 2019. <ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.wrestlinginc.com/news/2019/06/wwe-superstars-return-to-action-in-50-man-battle-royal-at-654969/ |title = WWE Superstars Return to Action at Super ShowDown, Updated List of Participants|date = June 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, AOP began appearing in vignettes, warning of their return. During the [[2019 WWE Draft]] in October, AOP went undrafted, becoming free agents and able to choose which brand to sign with. Three days after the draft's conclusion, AOP signed with Raw, remaining on the brand. Then, they started allying with [[Seth Rollins]] after they helped beat down [[Kevin Owens]] on the Raw after [[Survivor Series (2019)]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/videos/breaking-news-regarding-wwe-crown-jewel-free-agency-and-the-intercontinental-title-wwe-now|title=Breaking news regarding WWE Crown Jewel, free agency and the Intercontinental Title: WWE Now|date=October 17, 2019|work=[[WWE]].com|accessdate=October 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Championship and accomplishments ==\n* '''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n** Ranked No. 204 of the top 500 wrestlers in the [[PWI 500]] in 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=97&nr=230#2018|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated (PWI) 500 for 2018|accessdate=September 25, 2018|work=cagematch.net}}</ref>\n* '''[[WWE]]'''\n** [[NXT Tag Team Championship]] ([[List of NXT Tag Team Champions#Reigns|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[Rezar (wrestler)|Rezar]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/titlehistory/nxt-tag-team-championship|title=NXT Tag Team Championship|work=WWE|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n** [[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship]] ([[List of WWE Raw Tag Team Champions|1 time]]) \u2013 with Rezar<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/titlehistory/raw-tag-team-championship|title=Raw Tag Team Championship|work=WWE|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n** [[Dusty Rhodes Tag Team Classic]] (2016) \u2013 with Rezar\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{WWE superstar}}\n* {{Professional wrestling profiles}}\n\n{{WWE personnel}}\n{{WWE Tag Team Championship}}\n{{NXT Tag Team Championship}}\n{{Dusty Rhodes Tag Team Classic Winners}}\n\n[[Category:Canadian male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Canadian male sport wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Abbotsford, British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestlers from British Columbia]]\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Wrestlers at the 2011 Pan American Games]]\n[[