{"title_page": "Kathryn Evans", "text_new": "\n\n{{short description|British stage actress, singer and dancer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n<!--Note to editors: British stage actress Kathryn Evans is not the same person as British children's book writer Kathryn Evans.-->\n{{for|the British swimmer (born in 1981)|Kathryn Evans (swimmer)}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Kathryn Evans\n| birth_date         = 6 March 1952\n| birth_place        = [[London]], [[England]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n*Singer\n*Actress\n*Dancer\n}}\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Peter Purves]]|1982}}\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background         = solo_singer\n| instrument         = Vocals}}\n}}\n'''Kathryn Evans''' is a British [[Stage actress|stage actress]], [[singer]] and [[dancer]]. She trained at the [[Royal Ballet School|Royal Ballet School]] and [[Arts Educational]].\n\nShe is best known for being the final actress in London to play the lead role of Eva in the original production of [[Evita (musical)|Evita]]. She later appeared in many [[West End theatre|West End Theatre]] shows including [[Anything Goes]] in 1989-90 as Erma, [[Aspects of Love]] in 1993-94 as Rose Vibert, [[Mack & Mabel]] in 1995 and [[The Fix (musical)|The Fix]] in 1997.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20131002201327/http://www.whatsonstage.com/west-end-theatre/news/08-2002/20-questions-withkathryn-evans_27410.html 20 Questions with Kathryn Evans (archive.org: 2 Oct 2013)]</ref>\n\nShe played [[Norma Desmond]] in the West End revival of [[Sunset Boulevard (musical)|Sunset Boulevard]].<ref>[http://www.whatsonstage.com/index.php?pg=207&story=E8821229098530 Kathryn Evans On... Walking into Sunset] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081217235212/http://www.whatsonstage.com/index.php?pg=207&story=E8821229098530 |date=2008-12-17 }}</ref> She was nominated for an [[Olivier Award for Best Actress in a Musical]] for this role. In 2010, she appeared in [[42nd Street (musical)|42nd Street]] at the [[Chichester Festival Theatre]] in the lead role of Dorothy Brock.{{cn|date=June 2015}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Evans, Kathryn}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British stage actresses]]\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n\n\n{{England-stage-actor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British stage actress, singer and dancer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n<!--Note to editors: British stage actress Kathryn Evans is not the same person as British children's book writer Kathryn Evans.-->\n{{for|the British swimmer (born in 1981)|Kathryn Evans (swimmer)}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Kathryn Evans\n| background          = solo_singer\n| image               = \n| image_size          =\n| caption             = \n| birth_name          = \n| alias               =\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1952|03|06|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = London\n| origin              = [[London]], England, UK\n| spouse             = Peter Purves (1982-present)\n| death_date          =\n| occupation          = Singer, actress, dancer\n| Img size            = \n}}\n\n'''Kathryn Evans''' is a British stage actress, singer and dancer. She trained at the Royal Ballet School and Arts Educational.\n\nShe is best known for being the final actress in London to play the lead role of Eva in the original production of [[Evita (musical)|Evita]]. She later appeared in many [[West End theatre|West End Theatre]] shows including [[Anything Goes]] in 1989-90 as Erma, [[Aspects of Love]] in 1993-94 as Rose Vibert, [[Mack & Mabel]] in 1995 and [[The Fix (musical)|The Fix]] in 1997.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20131002201327/http://www.whatsonstage.com/west-end-theatre/news/08-2002/20-questions-withkathryn-evans_27410.html 20 Questions with Kathryn Evans (archive.org: 2 Oct 2013)]</ref>\n\nShe played [[Norma Desmond]] in the West End revival of [[Sunset Boulevard (musical)|Sunset Boulevard]].<ref>[http://www.whatsonstage.com/index.php?pg=207&story=E8821229098530 Kathryn Evans On... Walking into Sunset] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081217235212/http://www.whatsonstage.com/index.php?pg=207&story=E8821229098530 |date=2008-12-17 }}</ref> She was nominated for an [[Olivier Award]] for Best Actress in a Musical for this role. In 2010, she appeared in [[42nd Street (musical)|42nd Street]] at the [[Chichester Festival Theatre]] in the lead role of Dorothy Brock.{{cn|date=June 2015}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Evans, Kathryn}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British stage actresses]]\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n\n\n{{England-stage-actor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "CybJubal", "label": "safe", "comment": "Re-formatted for ease of reading", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kathryn_Evans"}
{"title_page": "24th Berlin International Film Festival", "text_new": "{{short description|Film festival}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox Film festival\n| name           = 24th Berlin International Film Festival\n| image          = 24th Berlin International Film Festival poster.jpg\n| caption        = Festival poster\n| opening        = \n| closing        = \n| location       = [[West Berlin]], Germany\n| founded        = 1951\n| awards         = [[Golden Bear]] (''[[The Apprenticeship of Duddy Kravitz (film)|The Apprenticeship of Duddy Kravitz]]'')\n| date           = 21 June \u2013 2 July 1974\n| website        = [http://www.berlinale.de Website]\n}}\nThe '''24th''' annual '''[[Berlin International Film Festival]]''' was held from 21 June \u2013 2 July 1974.<ref name=\"Berlinale 1974\">{{cite web |url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1974/01_jahresblatt_1974/01_Jahresblatt_1974.html |title=24th Berlin International Film Festival |accessdate=1 July 2010 |work=berlinale.de}}</ref> The Golden Bear was awarded to the Canadian film ''[[The Apprenticeship of Duddy Kravitz (film)|The Apprenticeship of Duddy Kravitz]]'' directed by [[Ted Kotcheff]].<ref name=\"PRIZES\" />\n\n==Jury==\nThe following people were announced as being on the jury for the festival:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1974/04_jury_1974/04_Jury_1974.html |title=JURIES 1974 |accessdate=8 June 2014 |work=berlinale.de | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131023110437/http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1974/04_jury_1974/04_Jury_1974.html| archivedate=23 October 2013 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n* [[Rodolfo Kuhn]], director and screenwriter - Jury President (Argentina)\n* [[Margaret Hinxmann]], writer and film critic (United Kingdom)\n* [[Pietro Bianchi (film critic)|Pietro Bianchi]], journalist and film critic (Italy)\n* [[G\u00e9rard Ducaux-Rupp]], producer (France)\n* [[Kurt Heinz]], composer (West Germany)\n* [[Akira Iwasaki]], historian and film critic (Japan)\n* [[Arthur Knight (film critic)|Arthur Knight]], historian and film critic (United States)\n* [[Manfred Purzer]], director and screenwriter (West Germany)\n* [[Piet Ruivenkamp]], film critic (Netherlands)\n\n==Films in competition==\nThe following films were in competition for the [[Golden Bear]] award:\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" width=\"95%\" cellpadding=\"5\"\n|-\n!width=\"25%\"| English title\n!width=\"25%\"| Original title\n!width=\"20%\"| Director(s)\n!width=\"30%\"| Country\n|-\n|''[[Ankur (film)|The Seedling]]''\n|''Ankur'' \n|[[Shyam Benegal]]\n|India\n|-\n|-style=\"background:#FFDEAD;\"\n|''[[The Apprenticeship of Duddy Kravitz (film)|The Apprenticeship of Duddy Kravitz]]'' \n|''The Apprenticeship of Duddy Kravitz''\n|[[Ted Kotcheff]]\n|Canada\n|-\n|''[[Rise, Fair Sun]]''\n|''Asayake no uta'' \n|[[Kei Kumai]]\n|Japan\n|-\n|''[[Bobby's War]]''\n|''Bobbys krig'' \n|[[Arnljot Berg]]\n|Norway\n|-\n|''[[Charley One-Eye]]'' \n|''Charley One-Eye''\n|[[Don Chaffey]]\n|United Kingdom\n|-\n|''[[The Conscript]]''\n|''De loteling'' \n|[[Roland Verhavert]]\n|Belgium\n|-\n|''[[The Love of Captain Brando]]''\n|''El amor del capit\u00e1n Brando'' \n|[[Jaime de Armi\u00f1\u00e1n]]\n|Spain\n|-\n|''[[A Handful of Love (film)|A Handful of Love]]''\n|''En handfull k\u00e4rlek'' \n|[[Vilgot Sj\u00f6man]]\n|Sweden\n|-\n|''[[Effi Briest (1974 film)|Effi Briest]]''\n|''Fontane \u2013 Effi Briest'' \n|[[Rainer Werner Fassbinder]]\n|Germany\n|-\n|\n|''[[Ha'Ya'ar Ha-Kasum]]'' \n|[[Shlomo Suriano]]\n|Israel\n|-\n|''[[In the Name of the People (1974 film)|In the Name of the People]]''\n|''Im Namen des Volkes'' \n|[[Ottokar Runze]]\n|Germany\n|-\n|''[[The Clockmaker]]''\n|''L'horloger de Saint-Paul'' \n|[[Bertrand Tavernier]]\n|France\n|-\n|''[[Rebellion in Patagonia]]''\n|''La Patagonia rebelde'' \n|[[H\u00e9ctor Olivera (film director)|H\u00e9ctor Olivera]]\n|Argentina\n|-\n|''[[The Pelican (film)|The Pelican]]''\n|''Le P\u00e9lican'' \